{"title": "36th Cavalry Division (Soviet Union)\n", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/36th_Cavalry_Division_(Soviet_Union)", "tags": ["Category:Cavalry divisions of the Soviet Union", "Category:Cavalry divisions of the Soviet Union in World War II", "Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1938", "Category:Soviet invasion of Poland", "Category:Use dmy dates from June 2017"], "text": "The 36th Cavalry Division was formed prior to 1939 and was assigned to the Belorussian Military District at the onset of Operation Barbarossa.\n\nWartime Service\nSoviet invasion of Poland\nAssigned to the 11th Army's 3rd Cavalry Corps for the invasion of Poland.\n\n1941\nThe division was located on the border of German-occupied Poland at the end of the invasion. This placed it in a position to be attacked by the Germans during the opening hours of the next phase.  On 22 June the division was ordered to form part of an Operations Group with the 6th Mechanized Corps to counterattack against the German forces.  It was attacked on 23 June by the Luftwaffe causing severe casualties among the troops and horses.  The division was effectively destroyed within 48 hours of the invasion and was officially disbanded on 6 July 1941.\n\nSubordinate Units\n24th Cavalry Regiment\n42nd Cavalry Regiment\n102nd Cavalry Regiment\n8th Tank Regiment (54 tanks and 3 armored cars)\n\nSee also\nCavalry Divisions of the Soviet Union 1917\u20131945\n\n\n== References =="}